Burda
Children to take over publishing house at 27
The new publishing boss Kallen is an interim solution: in the long term, Hubert Burda wants to put his company in the hands of his two children, he told SPIEGEL.
The holding company is to remain 100 per cent family-owned.
Hamburg - Publisher Hubert Burda sees his company in the hands of his children in the long term.
Both children will inherit at the age of 27 and have the firm intention of entering the company, the 69-year-old told SPIEGEL.
We have arranged the details of this as a precaution.
The question of whether they will also be active in the company will only arise afterwards.
Also the question of whether they are capable of doing so.
You cannot put your children in front of 7500 employees if they are not sufficiently capable.
That kills the children and the company as well.
Burda had announced on Thursday that he would retire from the chairmanship of the board as of January and appointed Paul-Bernhard Kallen as his successor.
The 52-year-old Kallen has been a member of Burda's board since 1999.
Initially, he was responsible for technology.
Later, responsibility for corporate assets was added with the treasury division and, after Jürgen Todenhöfer's departure, also for direct marketing, foreign countries, printing and finance.
For the first time, there is no family member at the helm of the publishing house.
Burda's children are 19 and 17 years old, his son Felix, who would be 42 today, died a few years ago.
The appointment of Kallen also serves to "bridge 10, 15 years," Burda said.
The holding company should continue to be 100 per cent owned by the family, Burda said.
Referring to the Schickedanz and Schaeffler cases, Burda said that even family businesses are not safe from going under: "That always affected families who let themselves be infected by a capital addiction, who completely speculated and thought they could rise to become a really big player.
That was never my strategy.
According to Burda, he "never had dreams of world power."
I don't see myself as the political preceptor of this country, as Springer was, and I don't want to play in the world league with 'Time' either, these shops have become too big.
